NOTES_ZEPHANIAH = {
    1: {
        1: 'HISTORICAL: Zephaniah\'s lineage is traced four generations back to Hezekiah, almost certainly the king of Judah (715–686 BC), making Zephaniah of royal descent — the only prophet explicitly linked to royalty. His ministry under Josiah (640–609 BC) likely preceded or accompanied the great reform of 621 BC. HEBREW: The name Zephaniah (tsephanyah, H6846) means "YHWH has hidden" or "YHWH has treasured," a fitting name for one who announces both judgment and a hidden remnant.',
        2: 'HEBREW: The phrase rendered "utterly sweep away" translates the Hebrew asoph aseph (H622), an infinitive absolute construction intensifying the verb — literally "gathering I will gather up" — conveying total, comprehensive collection for removal. THEOLOGICAL: This opening declaration sets a cosmic scope for the chapter, echoing the de-creation language of Genesis; what YHWH spoke into existence he now threatens to unsay.',
        3: 'TYPOLOGY: The reversal of the creation order — man, beast, birds, fish — directly inverts Genesis 1:20–28, presenting the Day of YHWH as an un-creation event. This pattern recurs in Jeremiah 4:23–26 and reaches its eschatological climax in Revelation 6:12–17. THEOLOGICAL: The inclusion of the fish of the sea is remarkable since no earlier judgment text (flood aside) extends to marine life; it underscores the totality of cosmic judgment.',
        5: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: "The host of the heavens" (tseva ha-shamayim, H6635/H8064) refers to the astral divine beings venerated across the ANE as members of the heavenly assembly. Worship of these beings was a direct violation of the Deuteronomy 32:8–9 ordering, in which YHWH alone is Israel\'s allotted divine patron. Milcom was the national deity of Ammon (1 Kgs 11:5), and swearing by him constituted allegiance-transfer to a foreign divine being.',
        7: 'HEBREW: "Be silent" translates has (H2013), an interjection calling for solemn, awe-struck stillness in the presence of divine action — used similarly in Habakkuk 2:20 and Zechariah 2:13. The image of YHWH preparing a "sacrifice" (zebach, H2077) with "consecrated guests" (qedoshim, H6918) is startling: Israel itself is the sacrifice, and the invited holy ones may refer to angelic agents of judgment. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The "consecrated guests" (qedoshim) invited to the divine sacrifice likely denotes members of the heavenly host called to execute YHWH\'s judicial decree, consistent with divine council warfare language throughout the prophets (cf. Isa 13:3; Jer 51:27–28).',
        12: 'HEBREW: "Thickening on their dregs" (qopheim al-shemareyhem, H7087/H8105) is a vivid winemaking metaphor: wine left undisturbed on its sediment grows thick, syrupy, and corrupted. The image depicts complacent, stagnant souls settled into spiritual inertia. THEOLOGICAL: Their functional deism — "YHWH will not do good, nor will he do evil" — is not atheism but practical denial of divine providence and governance, a theological posture the prophets consistently condemn (cf. Mal 2:17).',
        14: 'HEBREW: The phrase "hastening fast" (maher meod, H4116) communicates urgent velocity; the Day is not merely approaching but racing. The Hebrew continues with a rare, vivid line: "the sound of the day of YHWH — bitter (mar) is the warrior\'s cry there," personifying the Day as a sound, a voice, a battle shout. STRUCTURE: This verse functions as the hinge of the chapter\'s central poem (vv. 14–18), transitioning from announcement to visceral description in a crescendo of six paired descriptors across vv. 15–16.',
        15: 'TYPOLOGY: The six paired descriptors of the Day — wrath, distress/anguish, ruin/devastation, darkness/gloom, clouds/thick darkness — echo Joel 2:2 and directly inform New Testament apocalyptic, including Jesus\'s Olivet Discourse (Matt 24:29) and the Pauline "day of wrath" (Rom 2:5). The cumulative rhetorical weight is deliberate: no single image suffices to capture the totality of divine judgment. THEOLOGICAL: "Thick darkness" (araphel, H6205) is consistently associated in the OT with theophanic divine presence — paradoxically, YHWH\'s coming is simultaneously luminous terror and consuming darkness (cf. Exod 20:21; 1 Kgs 8:12).',
        18: 'THEOLOGICAL: The chapter closes with the phrase "in the fire of his jealousy" (be-esh qin\'ato, H784/H7068), a covenantal term: YHWH\'s jealousy (qin\'ah) is the passionate, exclusive claim of a covenant suzerain over his people, provoked by their allegiance to rival divine beings. TYPOLOGY: The language of consuming fire and sudden, total end anticipates both the Day of the Lord in 2 Peter 3:10–12 and the eschatological judgment of Revelation 19:11–21, where the Messiah executes the final divine council verdict upon the nations.',
    },
    2: {
        1: 'HEBREW: The opening imperative "hithqosheshu w\'qoshu" (gather and gather yourselves) uses a rare Hithpael reflexive form from qashas, meaning to collect oneself or assemble. The phrase "lo nikhsaph" (without shame/longing) is debated — it may mean a nation that feels no shame or a nation not yet desired/called. The repetition creates an urgent rhetorical summons before impending judgment.',
        3: 'HEBREW: The term \'anawim (meek/afflicted, Strong\'s H6041) carries covenantal weight, referring to the lowly remnant who depend wholly on YHWH rather than earthly power. "Perhaps you will be hidden" uses the verb satar (to conceal), the same root underlying the divine name El-Mistatter. TYPOLOGY: This remnant theology anticipates the Beatitudes (Matt 5:3-5), where Jesus pronounces blessing on the poor in spirit and the meek — the true \'anawim who inherit the earth.',
        7: 'THEOLOGICAL: The phrase "YHWH their God will attend to them" uses paqad — a covenantal visitation word implying both judgment and redemptive intervention. The promise to "restore their captivity" (shub shebut) is a classic prophetic restoration formula, signaling eschatological reversal. This verse grounds the judgment oracles of the chapter in YHWH\'s ultimate fidelity to his covenant people.',
        9: 'HISTORICAL: The invocation of Sodom and Gomorrah as the paradigm of total divine destruction (Gen 19) marks Moab and Ammon\'s fate as a recapitulation of primordial judgment. Significantly, Moab and Ammon were themselves descended from Lot, the sole survivor of Sodom, making this a deeply ironic reversal. THEOLOGICAL: The phrase "as I live — declares YHWH" (hay-ani ne\'um YHWH) is the divine oath formula, invoking YHWH\'s own existence as the guarantor of the pronouncement.',
        11: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: The declaration that YHWH "will make lean" (razah, to emaciate or reduce) all the gods (\'elohim) of the earth is a direct polemic against the divine council members assigned to the nations (cf. Deut 32:8-9; Ps 82). These are not mere idols of wood and stone but are treated as real spiritual entities whose power YHWH will diminish and destroy. This universal subjugation of the nations\' patron deities anticipates the cosmic Christus Victor theme of Col 2:15 and Phil 2:9-11.',
        13: 'HISTORICAL: The oracle against Nineveh, capital of the Assyrian empire, was delivered when Assyria was still a dominant world power. The city fell to the Babylonian-Median coalition in 612 B.C., fulfilling this prophecy with remarkable precision. Nahum prophesied the same destruction contemporaneously. TYPOLOGY: Nineveh\'s pride and sudden desolation (v. 15) serves as a type of Babylon in Revelation 18, where the same boast — "I sit as queen, and I am no widow" — meets a similar catastrophic end.',
        15: 'THEOLOGICAL: The taunt "I am, and there is none besides me" (\'ani we\'ephsi \'od) is the language of exclusive divinity — the precise phrasing YHWH uses of himself in Isaiah 45:5-6. Nineveh\'s appropriation of divine prerogatives constitutes the height of hubris and idolatrous self-deification. The hissing and shaking of the fist by passersby are ancient ANE gestures of contempt and mourning over a fallen city, paralleled in Lamentations 2:15.',
    },
    3: {
        1: 'HEBREW: The opening "hoy" (woe/alas; Strong\'s H1945) is a funeral lament particle, typically introducing oracles of doom. The city is described as "mora\'ah" (rebellious, H4805) and "nig\'alah" (defiled, polluted, H1351) — terms evoking ritual and moral corruption simultaneously. The identity of the city is Jerusalem, a striking reversal after oracles against the nations in chapters 1-2.',
        4: 'THEOLOGICAL: The indictment against prophets and priests as the primary agents of Torah-violence is a recurring covenantal theme (Jer 2:8; Ezek 22:26). The phrase "chamesu Torah" (they have done violence to the Torah) uses the same verb for violent injustice applied to social oppression, equating spiritual corruption with civic brutality. This sets the stage for the purified leadership of the restored remnant.',
        8: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: The language of YHWH rising as a witness ("le\'ed," H5707) and assembling the nations for judgment evokes the divine council courtroom scene (Ps 82:1; Deut 32:8-9). The outpouring of wrath upon assembled kingdoms carries cosmic-judicial overtones — YHWH as sovereign judge executing sentence upon nations under corrupt divine administration. TYPOLOGY: The eschatological gathering for judgment prefigures the final assize (Rev 16:14; Matt 25:32).',
        9: 'HEBREW: "Saphah berurah" — literally "a pure/clean lip." Saphah (H8193) means lip or language; berurah (H1305) means purified, refined. This is a direct reversal of the Babel event (Gen 11:1-9) where humanity\'s language was confused. THEOLOGICAL: The restoration of a pure tongue enabling unified worship anticipates Pentecost (Acts 2) and the eschatological gathering of all nations to call upon YHWH\'s name (Rom 10:13; Rev 7:9-10).',
        12: 'THEOLOGICAL: The preserved remnant is characterized by "ani" (humble, H6041) and "dal" (lowly, H1800) — terms describing economic and social marginalization as well as spiritual dependence. This inverts worldly standards of power and anticipates the beatitudes (Matt 5:3-5). The remnant\'s defining trait is refuge in YHWH\'s name, not human strength or institutional prestige.',
        13: 'TYPOLOGY: The portrait of the remnant — no injustice, no falsehood, no deceit — directly prefigures the servant community of Isaiah 53:9 and is cited in Revelation 14:5 regarding the 144,000 who follow the Lamb. The pastoral image of grazing and lying down without fear echoes the Good Shepherd motif (Ps 23; John 10:9-11), pointing to Messiah\'s reign.',
        15: 'THEOLOGICAL: The declaration "Melek Yisrael YHWH" — "the King of Israel, YHWH" — is a stunning royal affirmation. YHWH\'s kingship in the midst of Israel fulfills the ancient theocratic ideal (Ex 15:18; Num 23:21). TYPOLOGY: The NT identifies Jesus as this divine King present "in the midst" of his people (Matt 18:20; John 1:14; Rev 21:3), making this verse a significant Christological node.',
        17: 'THEOLOGICAL: Zephaniah 3:17 is one of the most dense restoration affirmations in the Hebrew canon. "Gibbor" (H1368, mighty warrior/champion) applied to YHWH in the midst of his people echoes Isaiah 9:6 where "El Gibbor" is a title of the messianic child-king. The verb "yachrish" (he will be quiet/silent) in love is debated — possibly indicating love so profound it transcends expression. HEBREW: "Yasis alayikh berinah" — he will spin/leap for joy over you with a ringing cry — employs the most exuberant vocabulary of celebration in the OT, applied remarkably to YHWH\'s own emotional response to his restored people.',
        19: 'TYPOLOGY: The gathering of the lame and the outcast mirrors Jesus\'s healings and table fellowship with marginalized persons (Luke 14:21; Matt 15:31), enacted demonstrations of the eschatological restoration Zephaniah envisions. The reversal of shame into praise and renown anticipates the honor bestowed upon the redeemed before all nations (Isa 62:7; Rev 21:26).',
        20: 'THEOLOGICAL: The book closes with YHWH\'s own first-person pledge: "I will restore your fortunes" (shavti et shevutkem) — the covenant restoration formula found throughout the prophets (Jer 29:14; 30:3; Amos 9:14). The phrase "before your eyes" (le\'eyneykhem) emphasizes the visible, historical, and publicly witnessed nature of this restoration, not merely a spiritual metaphor. This final promise anchors Zephaniah\'s cosmic Day of YHWH not in annihilation but in renewal.',
    },
}